The police have arraigned a 35-year-old man, Izuchukwu Okorom, at a Mararaba Upper Area Court in Nasarawa State, for alleged breach of trust and theft. Okorom, who resides at Mararaba, is facing a two-count charge of criminal breach of trust and theft, but he denied committing the offences. The police prosecutor, Sgt. Hemen Donald, told the court that one Jimoh Sunday of opposite Young Shall Grow Motors, Mararaba, reported the matter at the `A’ Police Division, Mararaba, on May 20. Donald said  the complainant alleged that the defendant stole his staff’s Itel phone. “Sometime in April 2018, the defendant entered the complainant’s shop at his address and borrowed the cashier’s phone with the intention of stealing it. “After stealing the phone, the defendant absconded to an unknown destination until he was seen and arrested on May 20, 2018,” Donald told the court. The prosecutor said the offences contravened sections 321 and 288 of the penal code. The judge, Ibrahim Shekarau, granted the defendant bail in the sum of N50,000 with one surety in like sum and adjourned the case until June 8 for hearing. (NAN)